

= Salesperson Roles in Sales and Trading

== Overview

Salespeople in Sales and Trading divisions are the primary client-facing professionals responsible for maintaining relationships with institutional investors, executing client trades, and generating revenue through commission and flow business. In Australia, sales roles exist at global investment banks (Goldman Sachs, J.P. Morgan, Morgan Stanley, UBS, Citi) and major Australian banks with institutional markets businesses (Macquarie Group, NAB, CBA, ANZ, Westpac).

Sales professionals bridge clients and trading desks - understanding client investment objectives, communicating market opportunities, executing trades, and providing market intelligence. Unlike traders who manage risk and make markets, or strategists who produce research, salespeople focus on relationships and revenue generation through client activity. The role combines relationship management, market knowledge, communication skills, and commercial acumen.

Post-GFC and post-Royal Commission, the sales role has evolved significantly with increased regulatory scrutiny around suitability and best execution, MiFID II research unbundling (affecting European clients), compression of trading margins driving need for higher volumes, and shift toward electronic execution requiring sales to add value through insights rather than just order-taking. Modern salespeople must be trusted advisors providing genuine value, not just order facilitators.

